If like me you were growing up in the India of the Seventies and Eighties, you will know why Lata Tai’s loss will forever change the timbre of India’s vocal chords. My piece in @thevofashion 

Posted @withregram • @thevofashion “Lataji’s voice expressed the million cross-wired sentiments, confusions and confidence of Independent India. It held a fond tremor for India’s soldiers. It raised money for cricket and children in need. Only she could evoke the gooseflesh shudders, the otherwise inexplicable realisation of being a patriotic Indian laden with the toils of sacrifice, the pride of martyrdom, the love, loss and longing of a nation as it was growing up.”
Independent India came of age as Lata Mangeshkar sang for 80 years, filling us with cheer and joy, to tears and truth, to faith and felicitation. And now she is silent. Read the full piece by TVOF editor-in-chief Shefalee Vasudev via the link in bio.

✒️ @shefatwork

Fashion & Flippancy
This is not to defend fashion blindly. It is to see it more clearly.
Fashion is linked with elitism, focus on celebrities, aggressive consumerism, capitalism, greenwashing in the name of sustainability. Valid issues. But is that all?  What about fashion as livelihood? As protest, identity and memory? What about young designers who cannot afford PR?
What about weavers, tailors, stylists? 
Perhaps it is time to see this "industry" beyond its popular projections?
Inviting debate.

Coming up next: TVOF readers weigh in on how fashion should deal with tragedy. 

🎤 @shefatwork

#thevofashion #nationalgriefandlifestylemedia

When Appearances Must Step Back: 
This is Not A Call Out. It’s a Call In after @thevofashion post yesterday on how fashion should speak.

In the absence of an ombudsman or an ethics committee for lifestyle media, content creation during natural calamities, accidents, disasters, terrorism and grief who decides tonality and what is sensitivity, is a matter of debate. Inviting senior editors, peers, designers and brand directors to weigh in. Without cancel culture, critique for effect or calling out, is this a moment for fashion media to find some answers? I also want to ask why is fashion considered flippant? Because of its obsession with appearance? Or because of the language we use?#fashionethics #fashionmedia #lifestylemedia #airindiacrash #nationalgriefawarenessday #nationaltragedies #editorspeak #mediaethics #griefandglamour #fashionresponsibility

The Voice of Fashion invites your thoughts on recalibrating content and voice, to walk the line between restraint, respect and reportage at this time of a national tragedy.
#AirIndiacrash

🎤 @shefatwork

The Silk Route has always fascinated me- not just as geography, but as shared memory,” says journalist, author, and psychotherapist @shefatwork , as she reflects on Obeetee’s new collection.

In her words, the Silk Route is more than an ancient trade network. It’s an intersection of art, ideas, myths, and materials- where motifs traveled across eras and civilizations, where imagination was traded alongside silks and spices.
She speaks of carpets as storytellers, capturing the imprint of climate, culture, prosperity, even famine.

A shared heritage that’s only meaningful when it’s passed down, recognised, and reimagined.

And through Silk Route, Obeetee invites us to trace those ancient lines once more- to see how far a motif can travel, and how deeply a thread can connect.

How Punjabi artists and singers have influenced global-local style. 
Punjabi music itself, high on volume and energy with lyrics packed with the names of cities and global luxury brands has become a subculture.
Their distinct style lexicon has spawned media articles, books, doctoral theses in South Asian culture. @diljitdosanjh with his style and popularity has taken this to a performative art. Many others bear this cosmopolitan twang. It filters down to sada Punjab where the influence Is unmissable.
Including and pertinently on Bhangra costume.

latestPosts.caption:
'The evening glittered with designers in “timeless couture”, the dress code for the 25th-anniversary gala of fashion weeks in India. Unlike most such events when a litany of Bollywood actors dominates runways, front rows, and parties, here designers were the stars. An artfully edited visual memoir on a large screen and a subjective interpretation of fashion’s evolution over a quarter century—are just a few ways to define the 25th anniversary of Lakmē Fashion Week. 
.
The show sashayed between the brilliant and the pedantic. In a way, it mirrored 25 years of Indian fashion—its unforgettable triumphs and its unmemorable creations. All of it unfolded as live performances—drummers, singers, artists from across genres—set the rhythm of the runway. Oddly, the show did not follow a chronological order. For spectators, it was perplexing to understand a clear narrative, if there was any. Garments from 2004 were abruptly followed by pieces from 2001, then 2017, with no apparent logic.
.
At Lakmē, the finale designer also directs a seasonal cosmetics collection—bold and big are a part of the brief. Expecting a democratic representation of fashion in this commemoration is perhaps misplaced. Yet by focusing only on theatrical couture, the show left out some of the biggest strides Indian designers have made in the past decade—especially in prêt or ready-to-wear.'

Link in bio to the article by Shefalee Vasudev (@shefatwork)

India’s textiles renaissance is slowly inflecting the story towards inclusivity. Producers and makers of Indian textile crafts still remain by and large marginal and ignored especially in attention, credits, recognition and earnings. These exhibitions are opening new ways of looking at their work, building new communities of curators, exhibition designers, thinkers, interdisciplinary artists. They underline the qualitative value of textiles beyond apparel and wearables. Beyond royal patronage and bridal. They bring the forgotten into the fold. They will nudge a new ecology.
